Capacity formula

To make things simpler, let’s consider only the ingredients of capacity that we have studied here as a function of age \(a\):

\[ C(a) \propto \frac{p(a) \times i(a)}{g(a)} e^{-\frac{g(a)}{m(a)}} \] Everything else will be a multiplicative constant. We don’t care too much about the exact values of such a constant because we will express everything relative to the 4-day-old group. Futhermore, in the results, we will learn from experiment 3 that \(m(a)\) does not change with age. So, for figure 5 we will be able to simply consider the following formula:

\[ C(a) \propto \frac{p(a) \times i(a)}{g(a)} e^{-\frac{g(a)}{m}} \] Sporozoite prevalences \(p(a)\) and sporozoite intensities (given infection) \(i(a)\) are informed by experiment 1, mosquitoes survival rates \(g(a)\) are informed by experiment 2 and the parasite maturation rate is informed by experiment 3. We will assume that the vector competence and survival and the parasite maturation are independent from each other. We’ll further assume that \(p(a)\) follows a beta distribution, the parameters of which will be estimated from the binomial estimate and its confidence interval from the presence/absence raw data and we will assume too that \(m\) follows a gamma distribution, the parameters of which are estimated in a similar way. Values for \(p(a)\) and \(m\) will then be randomly drawn from these beta and gamma distribution. Given that results from experiment 1 show that the distributions of sporozoites intensities do not look like any clear distribution, it will probably be better to perform non-parametric bootstrapping of the data in order to generate values of sporozoites intensities. As for the mosquito survival rates, we will simply compute the expected life expectancy from the non-parametrically boostrapped data.

Sporozoite prevalences

A function that converts confidence intervals boundary values of a proportion into parameters of a probability distribution:

ci2pars <- function(ci, f, pars, p = .95) {
  p <- (1 - p) / 2
  
  f_par <- function(par1, par2) {
    c(f(p, par1, par2), f(1 - p, par1, par2))
  }

  f_fit <- function(pars) {
    sum((f_par(pars[1], pars[2]) - ci)^2)
  }
  
  optim(pars, f_fit)$par
}

The shape parameters of the beta distribution of the mean sporozoites prevalences (\(p(a)\)):

p_par <- fig2 |> 
  group_by(age_class) |> 
  summarize(x   = sum(positive), n = length(positive)) |> 
  mutate(prop   = map2(x, n, prop.test),
         ci     = map(prop, magrittr::extract2, "conf.int"),
         shapes = map(ci, ci2pars, qbeta, 1:2)) |> 
  pull(shapes) |> 
  setNames(age_names)

Experiment 3

Loading and preparing the data:

fig4 <- "data/fig4_EIP_data.txt" |>
  read_delim() |> 
  select(dpi, spz) |> 
  na.exclude() |> 
  mutate_at("spz", as.logical)

The parameters of the gamma distribution that models the distribution of the maturation rate:

mod <- glm(spz ~ dpi, binomial, fig4)
invtransf <- family(mod)$linkinv

xs <- seq(min(fig4$dpi), max(fig4$dpi), le = 1000)
ys <- predict(mod, data.frame(dpi = xs), se.fit = TRUE)

ci <- tibble(xs  = xs,
             low = invtransf(ys$fit - 1.96 * ys$se.fit),
             upp = invtransf(ys$fit + 1.96 * ys$se.fit))

m <- 1 / ci2pars(c(filter(ci, .5 < upp)$xs[1],
                   filter(ci, .5 < low)$xs[1]), qgamma, 1:2)

Simulating data

The simulator of a distribution of values of the vectorial capacity:

simulate <- function(p, i, g, N = 10000) {
  p_val <- do.call(rbeta, c(list(N), unname(p)))
  i_val <- sample(i, N, replace = TRUE)
  g_val <- 1 / sample(g, N, replace = TRUE)
  m_val <- do.call(rgamma, c(list(N), m))
  p_val * i_val * exp(-g_val) / g_val
}

Peforming the simulations for the 4 groups:

sim_age4           <- simulate(p_par$`4-day-old`,   i$`4-day-old`, age4)
sim_age12_ExpInf   <- simulate(p_par$`12-day-old`, i$`12-day-old`, age12$`Exposed-infected`)
sim_age12_ExpNoinf <- simulate(p_par$`12-day-old`, i$`12-day-old`, age12$`Exposed-uninfected`)
sim_age12_Uninf    <- simulate(p_par$`12-day-old`, i$`12-day-old`, age12$`Uninfected control`)

Checking that stationarity has been reached:

walk(list(sim_age4, sim_age12_ExpInf, sim_age12_ExpNoinf, sim_age12_Uninf),
